{{Infobox award | name = St. Louis Walk of Fame | current_awards = | image = File:St-Louis-Walk-of-Fame-logo.jpeg | imagesize = | alt = St. Louis Walk of Fame logo | caption = St. Louis Walk of Fame logo | description = | presenter = | sponsor =Established by [[Joe Edwards (St. Louis)|Joe Edwards]] | host = | date = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | location = [[St. Louis]], [[Missouri]] | country = United States | reward = Brass star and bronze plaque embedded into the sidewalk along Delmar Boulevard | year = 1989 | year2 = | holder = | website = [http://www.stlouiswalkoffame.org/ stlouiswalkoffame.org] | previous = | main = | next = }} [[File:Walk-of-fame-joe-edwards.jpg|thumb|Chuck Berry's star in the St. Louis Walk of Fame]] The '''St. Louis Walk of Fame''' honors [[List of people from St. Louis|notable people from St. Louis]], [[Missouri]], who made contributions to the [[culture of the United States]]. All inductees were either born in the [[Greater St. Louis]] area or spent their formative or creative years there.<ref name="crit">{{cite web| author = Staff | url=http://www.stlouiswalkoffame.org/criteria/ |title=Nomination Criteria |publisher=St. Louis Walk of Fame |date= n.d. |accessdate= August 22, 2012}}</ref> Contribution can be in any area; most of the current inductees made their achievements in acting, entertainment, music, sports, art/architecture, broadcasting, journalism, science/education and literature.<ref>{{cite web| author = Database | date= n.d. | url= http://www.stlouiswalkoffame.org/inductees/?view=achievement |title= St. Louis Walk of Fame Inductees |publisher=St. Louis Walk of Fame | accessdate = August 22, 2012}}</ref>
{{as of|2017|6}}, the walk consisted of 147<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stlouiswalkoffame.org/inductees/|title=St. Louis Walk of Fame - Inductees|website=www.stlouiswalkoffame.org|access-date=2017-06-22}}</ref> brass stars and bronze plaques, each containing an inductee's name and a summary of his or her accomplishments. The stars and plaques are set into the sidewalks of [[Delmar Boulevard (St. Louis)|Delmar Boulevard]] in the [[Delmar Loop]] area, which is mostly in [[University City, Missouri|University City]], Missouri, an inner-ring suburb of St. Louis. The walk is about five miles (eight kilometers) west of the indoor [[Gateway Classic Walk of Fame]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://explorestlouis.com/visit-explore/member?mid=1012&c=43&member=Gateway%20Classic%20Walk%20of%20Fame |title=Gateway Classic Walk of Fame : St. Louis, MO |publisher=ExploreStLouis.com |date= |accessdate= March 17, 2010}}</ref> a recognition given by another organization, though some, including [[Dick Gregory]], [[Jackie Joyner-Kersee]], and [[Ozzie Smith]], have received hall of fame recognition from both St. Louis groups.<ref>{{Dead link|date=November 2010|bot=H3llBot}} {{cite web|url=http://www.gatewayclassic.org/fot.html |title=:: St. Louis Gateway Classic :: |publisher=Gatewayclassic.org |date= |accessdate= March 17, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://explorestlouis.com/media-page/news-releases-newsroom/releases/multicultural-st-louis/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111112075409/http://explorestlouis.com/media-page/news-releases-newsroom/releases/multicultural-st-louis/ |dead-url=yes |archive-date=November 12, 2011 |title=Multicultural St. Louis |publisher=ExploreStLouis.com |date= January 28, 2008 |accessdate= March 17, 2010}}</ref>
==Selection process== Anyone can submit a nomination by mail by supplying basic identification information as well as a description of the nominee's accomplishments and connection to St. Louis.<ref name="crit"/><ref name="commerce">{{cite web|url=http://www.stlcommercemagazine.com/archives/june2007/famous.html|title=Famous Folks – St. Louis History 101|date=June 2007|publisher=stlcommercemagazine.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080703233624/http://www.stlcommercemagazine.com/archives/june2007/famous.html|archive-date=2008-07-03|dead-url=yes|author=Caba, Susan|accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref> About 30 to 40 finalists are culled from the nominees by the walk's founder and director; the finalists are sent to a selection committee of 120 St. Louisans. The selection committee has been variously described as * "the chancellors of all area universities, key people from local libraries, arts organizations and historical societies, media journalists, and other citizens with an informed understanding of St. Louis' cultural heritage.".;<ref name="crit"/> or * "university chancellors, previous inductees and representatives of arts organizations, historical societies and libraries"<ref name="commerce"/>
Prior to 2007, the open-air induction ceremony was always been held the third week of May, though more recently it has depended on the availability of the latest inductees.<ref name="commerce"/>
==History== The walk was founded by developer [[Joe Edwards (St. Louis)|Joe Edwards]], owner of [[Blueberry Hill (restaurant)|Blueberry Hill]] pub/restaurant and other establishments located along the walk. Its first stars and plaques were installed in 1989; the inductees that year were musician [[Chuck Berry]], dancer and choreographer [[Katherine Dunham]], bridge builder [[James B. Eads]], poet [[T. S. Eliot]], ragtime composer [[Scott Joplin]], aviator [[Charles Lindbergh]], baseball player [[Stan Musial]], actor [[Vincent Price]], newspaper publisher [[Joseph Pulitzer]] and playwright [[Tennessee Williams]].<ref>{{dead link|date=March 2010}} [http://www.explorestlouis.com/media/factSheets/fact_walkOfFame.asp]. ExploreStLouis.com.</ref> Ten more were selected for each of the next four years (in order to get the walk established), but starting in 1994 no more than three have been awarded in any year.<ref name="commerce"/>
In May 2008, [[Cedric the Entertainer]] received the first star and plaque located in the City of St. Louis portion of the loop.<ref>{{cite web |last=Johnson |first=Kevin C. |url=http://www.stltoday.com/blogzone/the-blender/the-blender/2008/05/st-louis-walk-of-fame-welcomes-cedric-the-entertainer/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20080803002009/http://www.stltoday.com/blogzone/the-blender/the-blender/2008/05/st-louis-walk-of-fame-welcomes-cedric-the-entertainer/ |dead-url=yes |archive-date=August 3, 2008 |title=St. Louis Walk of Fame Welcomes Cedric the Entertainer |publisher=''The Blender'' (blog of the ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]'') |date=May 30, 2008 |accessdate=August 22, 2012 |df= }}</ref> The walk (and the boundaries of the Delmar Loop in general) has been expanded eastward by Edwards in recent years as Edwards continues to invest in the area's redevelopment.<ref name="commerce"/>
